            <!-- Education Section -->
<section id="education" class="education-section">
    <div class="education-container">
        <h2>Education: Learn About Diseases</h2>
        <p>Click on a disease to learn more about its symptoms, causes, and treatments.</p>

        <!-- List of Diseases with Information -->
        <div class="disease-list">
            <!-- Example Disease Items -->
            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">Flu (Symptoms: fever, cough, sore throat)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> The flu is a viral infection that attacks the respiratory system.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Caused by influenza viruses, often spread by respiratory droplets.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Rest, hydration, and over-the-counter medications to relieve symptoms. Consult a doctor if symptoms worsen.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">Diabetes (Symptoms: thirst, frequent urination)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> Diabetes is a chronic condition that affects how your body processes blood sugar (glucose).</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Type 1 diabetes is genetic, while Type 2 is often related to lifestyle and diet.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Medications, insulin therapy, and lifestyle changes, including diet and exercise.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">Heart Disease (Symptoms: chest pain, shortness of breath)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> Heart disease refers to conditions that affect the heart's structure and function.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> High blood pressure, high cholesterol, smoking, and genetic factors.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Medications, lifestyle changes, and possibly surgical procedures. Regular check-ups are essential.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">Tuberculosis (Symptoms: persistent cough, blood in sputum)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> Tuberculosis is a bacterial infection that primarily affects the lungs.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis bacteria, often spread through airborne droplets.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Antibiotic therapy, often requiring multiple medications over a period of several months.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">COVID-19 (Symptoms: fever, dry cough)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> COVID-19 is a viral respiratory disease caused by the SARS-CoV-2 virus.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Spread through respiratory droplets and close contact with infected individuals.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Symptomatic relief, hydration, rest, and isolation. Severe cases may require hospitalization.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">Cancer (Symptoms: unexplained weight loss, fatigue, pain)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> Cancer is a disease characterized by the uncontrolled growth of abnormal cells.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Genetic mutations, environmental factors, lifestyle, and exposure to carcinogens.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Chemotherapy, radiation therapy, surgery, and targeted therapy, depending on the type and stage of cancer.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">Pneumonia (Symptoms: cough, chest pain, fever)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> Pneumonia is an infection that inflames the air sacs in one or both lungs.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Bacterial, viral, or fungal infections. Often follows a respiratory infection.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Antibiotics for bacterial pneumonia, rest, fluids, and medication for symptomatic relief.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">Asthma (Symptoms: shortness of breath, wheezing)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> Asthma is a chronic respiratory condition characterized by inflamed and narrowed airways.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Allergens, exercise, cold air, and respiratory infections can trigger asthma attacks.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Inhalers, medications, and avoiding triggers. In severe cases, a doctor may prescribe steroids.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">Alzheimer's Disease (Symptoms: memory loss, confusion)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> Alzheimer's disease is a progressive neurological disorder that affects memory and cognitive function.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Age, genetics, and lifestyle factors contribute to Alzheimer's, though the exact cause is unknown.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> There is no cure, but medications and therapies can help manage symptoms and improve quality of life.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">Obesity (Symptoms: excess body weight, fatigue)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> Obesity is a condition characterized by excessive body fat that increases the risk of health problems.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Poor diet, lack of exercise, genetics, and lifestyle factors.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Lifestyle changes, dietary modifications, and physical activity. In severe cases, bariatric surgery may be considered.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">Arthritis (Symptoms: joint pain, stiffness)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> Arthritis is a condition that causes inflammation of one or more joints.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Age, wear and tear, autoimmune disorders, and infections.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Pain management, physical therapy, and anti-inflammatory medications. In some cases, joint surgery may be needed.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">AIDS (Symptoms: weight loss, night sweats, fatigue)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> AIDS is the final stage of HIV infection, leading to a severely weakened immune system.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Caused by HIV, a virus spread through bodily fluids.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Antiretroviral therapy (ART) can manage symptoms and slow the disease's progression, but there is no cure.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">Anemia (Symptoms: fatigue, pale skin)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> Anemia is a condition in which there is a lack of healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Iron deficiency, blood loss, or chronic disease.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Iron supplements, dietary changes, and addressing the underlying cause.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">Hypertension (Symptoms: headaches, vision problems)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> Hypertension is a chronic condition where blood pressure in the arteries is persistently elevated.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Lifestyle, genetics, stress, and diet.</p>
                    <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Medications, lifestyle changes, and dietary adjustments to reduce blood pressure.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="disease-item">
                <button class="disease-toggle">Malaria (Symptoms: fever, chills)</button>
                <div class="disease-info">
                    <p><strong>Description:</strong> Malaria is a life-threatening disease transmitted through the bite of an infected Anopheles mosquito.</p>
                    <p><strong>Causes:</

            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Chickenpox (Symptoms: itchy rash, fever)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Chickenpox is a highly contagious viral infection that causes an itchy, blister-like rash.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Caused by the varicella-zoster virus, often spread through respiratory droplets or direct contact.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Symptomatic relief, rest, hydration, and antiviral medications in severe cases.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Hepatitis B (Symptoms: fatigue, jaundice)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Hepatitis B is a viral infection that attacks the liver and can cause both acute and chronic disease.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Caused by the hepatitis B virus, spread through blood or bodily fluids.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Antiviral medications, rest, and liver function monitoring. Vaccination can prevent infection.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Ebola (Symptoms: fever, severe bleeding)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Ebola is a severe, often fatal illness affecting humans, caused by the Ebola virus.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Caused by the Ebola virus, spread through direct contact with bodily fluids.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Supportive care, including rehydration, and treating symptoms. No specific treatment is available.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Dengue Fever (Symptoms: high fever, joint pain)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Dengue fever is a mosquito-borne viral infection causing flu-like symptoms.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Spread by Aedes mosquitoes infected with the dengue virus.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Symptomatic treatment, hydration, and pain relievers. Severe cases require hospitalization.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Measles (Symptoms: rash, high fever)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Measles is a viral infection that spreads easily and causes a full-body rash and flu-like symptoms.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Caused by the measles virus, often spread through respiratory droplets.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Symptomatic treatment, rest, and hydration. Vaccination is available for prevention.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Multiple Sclerosis (Symptoms: numbness, fatigue)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Multiple sclerosis is a chronic illness that affects the central nervous system.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> The exact cause is unknown, but it is believed to be an autoimmune disorder.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Medications, physical therapy, and symptom management.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Parkinson's Disease (Symptoms: tremors, stiffness)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Parkinson's disease is a progressive nervous system disorder that affects movement.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> The cause is unknown but may involve genetic and environmental factors.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Medications, surgery, and lifestyle changes to manage symptoms.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Cholera (Symptoms: severe diarrhea, dehydration)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Cholera is an infectious disease that causes severe watery diarrhea, which can lead to dehydration.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Caused by ingesting food or water contaminated with Vibrio cholerae bacteria.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Rehydration, antibiotics, and zinc supplements in severe cases.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Bronchitis (Symptoms: persistent cough, mucus)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Bronchitis is an inflammation of the lining of the bronchial tubes, which carry air to and from the lungs.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Caused by viruses, often the same ones that cause colds and flu.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Symptomatic treatment, hydration, and rest. Antibiotics are not effective for viral bronchitis.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Gout (Symptoms: intense joint pain, inflammation)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Gout is a form of arthritis characterized by sudden, severe attacks of pain and swelling in joints.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Caused by high levels of uric acid in the blood.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Anti-inflammatory medications, lifestyle changes, and a low-purine diet.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Lupus (Symptoms: fatigue, joint pain)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Lupus is an autoimmune disease that causes inflammation in various parts of the body.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Exact cause unknown, but genetics and environmental triggers play a role.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Immunosuppressants, anti-inflammatory drugs, and lifestyle modifications.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Hemophilia (Symptoms: prolonged bleeding)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Hemophilia is a rare disorder in which the blood doesnâ€™t clot normally.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Genetic mutation that affects blood clotting proteins.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Replacement therapy with clotting factor concentrates.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Cystic Fibrosis (Symptoms: thick mucus, chronic cough)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Cystic fibrosis is a genetic disorder that affects the lungs and digestive system.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Caused by a mutation in the CFTR gene.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Chest physical therapy, medications, and nutritional support.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Huntington's Disease (Symptoms: movement disorders, cognitive decline)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Huntington's disease is an inherited disorder that causes progressive breakdown of nerve cells in the brain.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Caused by a genetic mutation.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Medications for symptom management, but no cure exists.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="disease-item">
            <button class="disease-toggle">Sickle Cell Anemia (Symptoms: pain, fatigue)</button>
            <div class="disease-info">
                <p><strong>Description:</strong> Sickle cell anemia is a genetic blood disorder where red blood cells assume an abnormal, rigid shape.</p>
                <p><strong>Causes:</strong> Inherited gene mutation.</p>
                <p><strong>Treatment:</strong> Pain management, blood transfusions, and hydroxyurea.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
        </div>
